    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-29T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-29T20:00:00-05:00" n="920"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d920">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">892.01/12–3044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-30T08:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 30, 1944—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 12:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2086. Foreign Office informs us in strict confidence that two groups of Thai
                    nationals, one civil and one military, have arrived in Kunming secretly from
                    Thailand for talks with Chinese Government officials and that head of civil
                    group bears an autographed letter from Thai Premier.<note n="3" xml:id="d920fn1"
                        >Khuang Aphaiwong.</note> Foreign Office desires to ascertain views of
                    American Government as to how to deal with the delegation and what general lines
                    of policy should be pursued. Foreign Office states arrangements will be made in
                    due course after delegation’s arrival in Chungking for us to meet them
                    informally and is making similar approach to British Embassy.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Foreign Office states no objection to informing Thai Minister.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d920fn2">Mom Rajawongse Seni Pramoj.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
